  2. Notes to the Schedule of Expenditures of Federal Awards (SEFA)
  Note 1:  Describe the significant accounting policies used in preparing the SEFA. (2 CFR 200.510(b)(6))
      The accompanying schedule of expenditures of federal awards (the Schedule) includes the federal award activity of College of DuPage under programs of the federal government for the year ended June 30, 2020. The information in this Schedule is presented in accordance with the requirements of 2 CFR Part 200, Uniform Administrative Requirements, Costs Principles, and Audit Requirements for Federal Awards (Uniform Guidance). Because the Schedule presents only a selected portion of the operations of College of DuPage, it is not intended to and does not present the financial position, changes in net assets, or cash flows of College of DuPage. Expenditures reported on the Schedule are reported on the accrual basis of accounting. Such expenditures are recognized following the cost principles contained in the Uniform Guidance wherein certain types of expenditures are not allowable or are limited as to reimbursement. Negative amounts shown on the Schedule represent adjustments or credits made in the normal course of business to amounts reported as expenditures in prior years. 4,000 characters

  5. Text of the Audit Findings      
  a. Audit Finding Reference Number     b. Audit Finding Text
               
2020-001     2020-001 – Awarding of Aid to Eligible Applicants

Federal agency: U.S. Department of Education
Major Program: Student Financial Assistance Cluster
CFDA Number: 84.033 – Federal Work-Study Program

Award Period: July 1, 2019 to June 30, 2020

Type of Finding:  Significant Deficiency in Internal Control Over Compliance

Criteria:
The Code of Federal Regulations 34 CFR § 668.32(f) states that a student is eligible to receive Title IV, HEA program assistance if the student maintains satisfactory academic progress in his or her course of study according to the institution’s published standards of satisfactory academic progress that meet the requirements of § 668.34.

Condition:
During our testing of satisfactory academic progress as it relates to Title IV eligibility, we noted 1 out of 40 students that received Title IV assistance while on suspension as a result of not maintaining satisfactory academic progress.

Questioned costs: $1,446

Cause:
The College feels that the cause of this finding had to do with the multiple changes in staffing and leadership due to retirements and attrition that occurred in the Financial Aid Office, and the lack of high-level oversight that the Federal Work Study Program typically received.

Effect:
The College is not in compliance with Department of Education Title IV, HEA program assistance eligibility requirements for ensuring applicant eligibility prior to disbursing Title IV funds.

Repeat Finding: No

Recommendation:
We recommend that the College review its procedures related to Title IV, HEA program assistance eligibility to ensure aid is being disbursed to eligible applicants only.

Management’s Response:
It is the College’s belief that this finding was an isolated incident caused by the staffing and leadership changes in the Financial Aid Office. As an institution, we are enhancing and strengthening our current written procedures for monitoring students’ eligibility and cross-training additional staff to ensure that we do not repeat this finding in the future.

  PART IV: CORRECTIVE ACTION PLAN  
  1. Audit Finding Reference Number     2. Text of the Corrective Action Plan
           
2020-001     2020-001 – Awarding of Aid to Eligible Applicants

Recommendation: We recommend that the College review its procedures related to Title IV, HEA program assistance eligibility to ensure aid is being disbursed to eligible applicants only.

Planned Corrective Action: It is the College’s belief that this finding was an isolated incident caused by the staffing and leadership changes in the Financial Aid Office. As an institution, we are enhancing and strengthening our current written procedures for monitoring students’ eligibility and cross-training additional staff to ensure that we do not repeat this finding in the future.

Contact People Responsible for Corrective Action:
Dr. Diana Del Rosario, Assistant Provost, Student Affairs
Nishia Ikezoe Heard, Senior Director, Student Financial Assistance, Veterans Services & Scholarships
Scott Brady, Interim CFO & Treasurer

Anticipated Completion Date: June 30, 2021		  
     
          10,000 characters    
           
2020-002     0020-002 – Enrollment Status Reporting

Recommendation: We recommend that the College review its procedures to ensure enrollment status changes are reported to NSLDS accurately and timely as required by regulations.

Planned Corrective Action: The College of DuPage has reviewed and agrees with the enrollment reporting finding and has already taken multiple steps to resolve all issues ensuring complete, accurate and timely reporting. The College has done or will do the following:

1. Proper training and procedures have been written ensuring that all reporting errors are properly resolved. The College has begun resubmitting student records, they have been reviewed in NSLDS and verified that all required changes occurred on a program and campus level for these students.
2. Under the leadership of a new Registrar, the policy and procedure for processing COVID related withdrawals has been changed. The Registrar’s Office no longer uses the date the COVID withdrawal was processed as the student’s official withdrawal date. The official withdrawal date will be the date the student officially submits their withdrawal request, the same as all other withdrawal submittals.
3. Work is in progress to resolve IT issues regarding the use of preferred first name versus legal name.
4. Short term and long term resolutions are being implemented to resolve those students who were submitted with a failing grade and a last date of attendance. In the short term, those students will be manually updated in NSLDS. In the long term, discussions are underway to change the current grading policy since the College already has other policies and procedures to capture official and unofficial withdrawals and transmit those enrollment changes to NSLDS.

Contact People Responsible for Corrective Action:
Dr. Diana Del Rosario, Assistant Provost, Student Affairs
Nishia Ikezoe Heard, Senior Director, Student Financial Assistance, Veterans Services & Scholarships
Cesar Flores, Interim Dean of Enrollment
Scott Brady, Interim CFO & Treasurer

Anticipated Completion Date: June 30, 2021
